{
  "id": "study-nyc-garage-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "NYC Garage — Body and Soul",
  "subtitle": "The rhythm that made the Paradise Garage move",
  "annotation": "The NYC garage pattern is built around the interplay between the clap and the open hat. The clap lands hard on 2 and 4 — this is not a Chicago snare, it is a statement. The open hat rides on the 'a' of every single beat, a relentless forward motion that the closed hat 8ths alone cannot provide. This is the pattern that sounds simple until you try to replace the open hat with anything else: without it, the groove collapses. The kick stays on every downbeat, not driving, accompanying. The entire pattern is in service of the dance floor, not the producer's cleverness.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Soft 16-tick push. The off-beats lean into the bar without rushing. Lilt, not swing.",
    "accentLogic": "Clap owns beats 2 and 4. Open hat creates continuous motion. Kick serves the room.",
    "microtimingTendencies": "Open hats arrive slightly behind the grid. The clap is spot-on. The contrast creates the feel."
  },
